{
  "texts": [
    "B.1 Implementing reflections about arbitrary statesA common use of state preparation within larger algorithms is to perform a reflection about a particular state |ψ⟩, that is, the operationR = I n -2 |ψ⟩ ⟨ψ|, (37)where I n denotes the identity operator on n qubits.",
    "We now discuss how to implement this operator using U.",
    "First, we make a distinction between different ancilla registers in our state-preparation protocol.",
    "For the SP portion of the protocol, we have ancilla registers A and F, each of size M -1, depicted in Fig. 7.",
    "For the CSP portion, we have an additional register B of size N/M -1 (register F is the same as the one from the SP portion)."
  ]
}